# Dictum — Licensing

Dictum is licensed in **two parts, by content type**. Which license applies to
a file depends on what the file *is*. The rule is by directory:

> **Files under `skills/`, `agents/`, and `templates/` are MIT.**
> **Every other file (the standard's prose) is CC BY 4.0.**

---

## 1. The standard (prose) — CC BY 4.0

Copyright © 2026 David H. Jung and the Dictum contributors.

The normative text of the Dictum standard is licensed under the **Creative
Commons Attribution 4.0 International License (CC BY 4.0)**.

- Full legal text: [`LICENSES/CC-BY-4.0.txt`](LICENSES/CC-BY-4.0.txt)
- Human-readable summary: <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/>

**Covered:** `STANDARD.md`, `GLOSSARY.md`, `failure-mode-catalog.md`,
everything under `concerns/`, and the project's prose documentation
(`README.md`, `ROADMAP.md`, `WORKFLOWS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `POSITIONING.md`).

You are free to **share** (copy and redistribute in any medium or format) and
**adapt** (remix, transform, and build upon the material) for any purpose,
including commercially — provided you **give appropriate credit**, link to this
license, and **indicate if changes were made**. You may not imply the project
endorses you or your use.

**One authoritative version — guaranteed by name and provenance, not by copyright.**
CC BY intentionally lets anyone adapt or translate the text. What keeps a single
canonical standard is not a copyright restriction but two other mechanisms:

- the **name** "Dictum" and a version identifier are reserved to the official
  text published from the canonical repository (see [`TRADEMARK.md`](TRADEMARK.md)); and
- each release is **published from the canonical source with a checksum/signature**
  (see [`RELEASES.md`](RELEASES.md)), so "Dictum v*X*" can be verified as authentic.

An adaptation is therefore permitted, but — per CC BY — it must credit this
source and mark its changes, and — per the name policy — it may not call itself
"Dictum" or present itself as the official standard.

**What this does not restrict:** *Applying* Dictum to document your own product
is not even an adaptation of the text — you may use the method freely, write your
own product's docs with it, ship products built from those docs, and build tools
around it, with no obligation at all.

## 2. The tooling and templates (code) — MIT

The Claude Code tooling and the fill-in templates are licensed under the **MIT
License**.

- Full text: [`LICENSES/MIT.txt`](LICENSES/MIT.txt) (also copied into each of
  `skills/`, `agents/`, and `templates/` so it travels with the files when they
  are copied into your own repository).

**Covered:** everything under `skills/`, `agents/`, and `templates/`.

These are meant to be copied into your own repositories and adapted. MIT lets
you do that with attribution and no further obligation.

## 3. The name "Dictum" and release provenance

Copyright and naming are **separate**. The CC BY license grants no rights in the
**"Dictum"** name — and the project claims **no registered trademark** and does not
intend to register one; the name is a **first-mover naming convention** (see
[`TRADEMARK.md`](TRADEMARK.md)). What actually identifies the official standard is
**provenance**: releases published from the canonical repository with a verifiable
signature/checksum (see [`RELEASES.md`](RELEASES.md)). Under CC BY 4.0 (§2(b)) no
trademark rights are licensed either way.

## 4. Contributions

Contributions are welcome and are accepted under the terms in
[`CONTRIBUTING.md`](CONTRIBUTING.md). Prose contributions are made under the same
**CC BY 4.0** as the standard (inbound = outbound); tooling and template
contributions are under **MIT**. Both are affirmed by a Developer Certificate of
Origin sign-off. Contributors retain copyright in their contributions.

---

### SPDX summary

